<DocsLayout title="Agent Integration — sift" currentPath="/agents/">
  <h1>Agent Integration</h1>
  <p class="subtitle">
    Set up conversational task management with Claude Code, Claude Desktop, or OpenCode.
  </p>

  <p>
    Sift integrates with AI coding agents so you can manage your Obsidian tasks through
    natural conversation. Ask your agent about your tasks, add new ones, mark things done,
    and manage projects — all without switching context.
  </p>

  <div class="conversation-demo">
    <pre>{agentConversation}</pre>
  </div>

  <h2>How it works</h2>
  <p>
    Sift provides tools that your AI agent can call. The agent sees the tool descriptions,
    decides when to use them based on your conversation, and calls the <code>sift</code> CLI under the hood.
  </p>

  <h3>Available tools</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Tool</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>sift_list</code></td><td>List open tasks with optional search/priority/date filters</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>sift_next</code></td><td>Get the most important tasks sorted by urgency</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>sift_summary</code></td><td>Quick overview of task status</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>sift_add</code></td><td>Add a task to today's daily note or a project</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>sift_find</code></td><td>Search tasks without modifying them</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>sift_done</code></td><td>Mark a task as complete (by search or precise file:line)</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>sift_projects</code></td><td>List all projects in the vault</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>sift_projectCreate</code></td><td>Create a new project from template</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>sift_projectPath</code></td><td>Get the file path for a project</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>sift_addNote</code></td><td>Add a freeform note to a daily note or project</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>
    Tool names use underscores in MCP (e.g., <code>sift_project_create</code>)
    and camelCase in OpenCode (e.g., <code>sift_projectCreate</code>).
  </p>

  <h2>Setup for Claude Code / Claude Desktop</h2>
  <p>
    Claude Code and Claude Desktop use the
    <a href="https://modelcontextprotocol.io/">Model Context Protocol (MCP)</a>.
    Sift runs as a local MCP server that exposes its tools.
  </p>

  <pre><code># 1. Build everything (CLI + MCP server)
npm install
npm run build

# 2. Link sift globally so the MCP server can find it
npm link --workspace=packages/cli

# 3. Configure your vault (if not already done)
sift init "/path/to/your/vault"

# 4. Run the install script
./scripts/install-agent-claude.sh

# 5. Restart Claude Desktop and/or Claude Code</code></pre>

  <p>The install script automatically updates:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Claude Desktop:</strong> <code>~/Library/Application Support/Claude/claude_desktop_config.json</code></li>
    <li><strong>Claude Code:</strong> <code>~/.claude.json</code></li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Manual configuration</h3>
  <p>If you prefer to configure manually, add this to your Claude config:</p>
  <pre><code>{JSON.stringify({
    mcpServers: {
      sift: {
        command: "node",
        args: ["/path/to/sift/packages/agent-skill/dist/mcp-server.js"]
      }
    }
  }, null, 2)}</code></pre>

  <p>
    If <code>sift</code> isn't on your PATH, add <code>SIFT_CLI_PATH</code> to the <code>env</code> section
    pointing to the built CLI entry point.
  </p>

  <h2>Setup for OpenCode</h2>
  <p>
    <a href="https://opencode.ai">OpenCode</a> uses a skill + custom tools model.
    The skill tells the agent what sift does and when to use it; the tools define what it can call.
  </p>

  <pre><code># 1. Build the CLI
npm install
npm run build

# 2. Make sure sift is on your PATH
npm link --workspace=packages/cli

# 3. Configure your vault (if not already done)
sift init "/path/to/your/vault"

# 4. Install the skill and tools
./scripts/install-agent.sh

# 5. Restart OpenCode</code></pre>

  <p>The install script copies files to:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><code>~/.config/opencode/skills/sift/SKILL.md</code></li>
    <li><code>~/.config/opencode/tools/sift.ts</code></li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Manual setup</h3>
  <pre><code>mkdir -p ~/.config/opencode/skills/sift
cp packages/agent-skill/SKILL.md ~/.config/opencode/skills/sift/SKILL.md
cp packages/agent-skill/tools/sift.ts ~/.config/opencode/tools/sift.ts</code></pre>

  <h2>Keeping things up to date</h2>
  <p>
    When you make changes to sift, you'll need to redeploy the agent tools:
  </p>

  <h3>For Claude Code / Claude Desktop</h3>
  <pre><code>npm run build --workspace=packages/agent-skill
# Then restart Claude Desktop and/or Claude Code</code></pre>

  <h3>For OpenCode</h3>
  <pre><code>./scripts/install-agent.sh
# Then restart OpenCode</code></pre>

  <h2>What you can say</h2>
  <p>
    Once set up, your AI agent will automatically recognize task-related requests.
    Here are some examples:
  </p>

  <div class="prompt-grid">
    <div class="prompt-card">
      <h4>Check in</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>"What's on my plate?"</li>
        <li>"What should I work on next?"</li>
        <li>"Show me my overdue tasks"</li>
        <li>"How many tasks do I have open?"</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="prompt-card">
      <h4>Add tasks</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>"Add a task to review the PR by Friday"</li>
        <li>"Remind me to submit expenses"</li>
        <li>"Add a high-priority task to the Website project"</li>
        <li>"I need to prepare the demo slides for Monday"</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="prompt-card">
      <h4>Complete tasks</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>"Mark the quarterly report as done"</li>
        <li>"I finished the architecture review"</li>
        <li>"Done with the PR"</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="prompt-card">
      <h4>Projects & notes</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>"What projects do I have?"</li>
        <li>"Add a note to Website Redesign"</li>
        <li>"Create a new project called 'Q2 Planning'"</li>
        <li>"What's in the Health Tracker project?"</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>CWD project context</h2>
  <p>
    If your code repository has a <code>.siftrc.json</code> with a <code>project</code> field,
    agents will be aware of the associated vault project. They'll suggest routing tasks to that
    project when appropriate and show the context in summaries.
  </p>
  <pre><code>{JSON.stringify({ project: "Website Redesign" }, null, 2)}</code></pre>

  <h2>Safe task completion</h2>
  <p>
    Agents follow a two-step flow to prevent accidentally marking the wrong task:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Search first</strong> — the agent calls <code>sift_find</code> to locate the task and shows you the match</li>
    <li><strong>Confirm</strong> — you verify it's the right task</li>
    <li><strong>Complete precisely</strong> — the agent calls <code>sift_done</code> with the exact file path and line number</li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    This means you'll never accidentally complete the wrong task, even if multiple tasks have similar descriptions.
  </p>
